title: Late 19th Century Emerald Green Florentine Cameo Art Satin Glass Vase

Florentine cameo vases, mostly made in Florence, Italy, were made as less expensive alternatives to cameo vases coming out of England. title: Mid-Century Modern Vintage Industrial 3 Light Can Lamp
description: Someone made clever use of everyday materials and combined them with this little 3 light can lamp to make it quite literally a can lamp.  The overall proportions and aesthetic effect are surprisingly pleasant.  You really don't notice at first because it looks like it was made that way.  Then, once you do, you are delighted with the creativity and artistry that led to this lovely piece.

title: Vintage 1940s Round Scrolling Ceiling Light Fixtures With Chipped Paint Patina - a Pair
description: This lovely little pair of flush mount ceiling light fixtures feature beautiful scrolling details, refurbished bulb sockets, and authentically chippy paint. Leave as is for that lovely aged look or give them a quick scrub for a cleaner style. From an original Victorian hanging fixture, these pieces have been cleverly reimagined and refurbished into a lovely flush mount style that will look stunning set inside of a beautifully ornate ceiling medallion. Regardless, this pair of fixtures make a stunning and classic pair for many different spaces.

description:
This monumental brilliant cobalt blue mid-century modern lamp strikes a stunning balance between simple and traditional with its sleek gently lilting curves and the repeating pattern with a motif that is reminiscent of a nautilus shell or fleur de lis. 

The last few photos depict the shade I originally have paired with another lamp for reference to help you decide a nice size shade to go with this lamp. For reference the shade is 14.25" wide by 17.25" tall.

title: Antique Primitive Sawbuck Cooks Tea Table
description: This stunning early american primitive mid-19th century saw buck cook's table has such incredible wear and patina, you won't believe your eyes.  The table top has gorgeous different sized pieces of lumber pieced together, and features beautiful signs of wear, patina and usage, including a character enhancing burn mark.  on the bottom square nuts and a wooden peg on the outside of either end hold the legs together.  It dates somewhere around 1850-1870.  It's a wonderful size for a small dining table or even potentially a large side table.  Don't let this one get away, or you'll be dreaming of it for years to come.

We can see this lamp in many settings, from maximalist to organic modern and beyond.
